00:00:00.200 --> 00:00:03.060
Last time I left you with a cliffhanger,
right?

00:00:03.060 --> 00:00:07.850
So we better try to resolve that,
the two envelope problem.

00:00:07.850 --> 00:00:11.590
So, I'll remind you what the problem is,
it's very simple to state, but not so

00:00:11.590 --> 00:00:13.190
easy to resolve.

00:00:13.190 --> 00:00:19.938
So the problem is just, we have two
envelopes, envelope one, envelope two.

00:00:19.938 --> 00:00:28.072
They look identical, and suppose they are
X dollars in here and Y dollars in here.

00:00:28.072 --> 00:00:30.172
And you don't know anything
at all about X and

00:00:30.172 --> 00:00:33.200
Y, just they're random
variables right now.

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:37.642
And all you know is that one envelope
has twice as much money as the other.

00:00:41.359 --> 00:00:44.750
So they each have a check for
some amount of money.

00:00:44.750 --> 00:00:46.080
And one is double the other.

00:00:46.080 --> 00:00:51.640
But you have no information other than
that, twice as much as the other, okay.

00:00:53.240 --> 00:00:58.570
So the argument last time was,
Let's say you get to pick one.

00:00:58.570 --> 00:01:02.140
So let's say you pick this one,
and this one's X.

00:01:02.140 --> 00:01:04.920
And you don't know what
X is unless you open it.

00:01:04.920 --> 00:01:09.430
But you do know,
the other one is either 2X or X over 2.

00:01:09.430 --> 00:01:13.073
And if you average 2X and X over 2,
you get a number bigger than X,

00:01:13.073 --> 00:01:15.710
which suggests that this one is better.

00:01:15.710 --> 00:01:18.150
But you could reply the same
argument to this one.

00:01:18.150 --> 00:01:21.369
This one's a Y,
the other one's 2Y or one-half Y.

00:01:21.369 --> 00:01:24.290
If you average 2Y and one-half Y,
you get a number bigger than Y.

00:01:24.290 --> 00:01:25.460
So, all right.

00:01:25.460 --> 00:01:28.945
So, let's actually write that out
kinda formally as an argument.

00:01:28.945 --> 00:01:31.698
So, based on the other two
competing arguments here.

00:01:31.698 --> 00:01:38.059
Argument one, Is

00:01:38.059 --> 00:01:43.603
simply that E(Y) = E(X) by symmetry.

00:01:48.248 --> 00:01:52.348
So, if you were given some
piece of information that

00:01:52.348 --> 00:01:57.301
the person who put the money in
the envelopes is left-handed.

00:01:57.301 --> 00:02:00.786
And left-handed people subconsciously
wanna put more money on the left, or

00:02:00.786 --> 00:02:03.902
something like that, then you'd
have an asymmetry in the problem.

00:02:03.902 --> 00:02:08.720
But there was no asymmetry given, that
the way it was stated is just there's no

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:13.100
difference that the left envelope
should have more or the right one, so

00:02:13.100 --> 00:02:15.150
it's a symmetrical situation.

00:02:17.830 --> 00:02:20.610
It's kind of hard to argue
against symmetry here, right?

00:02:20.610 --> 00:02:23.020
There is no asymmetry in
the statement of the problem, so

00:02:23.020 --> 00:02:27.080
if somehow the envelope on the left were
better, where would that have come from?

00:02:27.080 --> 00:02:28.236
It doesn't make sense, okay?

00:02:28.236 --> 00:02:30.950
So that's a pretty strong argument.

00:02:30.950 --> 00:02:33.970
But let's look at argument 2,
which also seems pretty strong.

00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:37.420
Argument 2 is the condition.

00:02:40.670 --> 00:02:43.080
Say how do we compute expectation?

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:46.120
Just like when we had a probability,
we didn't know.

00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:49.616
We want a condition on
the thing we wish that we knew.

00:02:49.616 --> 00:02:53.412
And so this is just the law of total
probability except the expectation

00:02:53.412 --> 00:02:54.330
version.

00:02:54.330 --> 00:02:57.630
We're gonna condition on whether,

00:03:00.604 --> 00:03:04.950
You know either Y = 2x or Y = one-half X.

00:03:04.950 --> 00:03:06.900
So we could just write it this way.

00:03:06.900 --> 00:03:14.114
E(Y|Y=2x) P(Y=2x) + E(Y|Y=
one-half X)P(Y= one-half X).

00:03:14.114 --> 00:03:22.802
So I mean that's just a fact about
expectation that you condition.

00:03:22.802 --> 00:03:27.858
And the proof of this is basically just

00:03:27.858 --> 00:03:35.400
use the law of total probability,
and that's true.

00:03:35.400 --> 00:03:37.420
So it's hard to argue with that.

00:03:37.420 --> 00:03:38.960
Let's compute this.

00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:48.750
So the argument goes, E(Y|Y=2x),
well, then we know Y = 2x.

00:03:48.750 --> 00:03:53.444
So we're just gonna replace
that with E(2x) by symmetry.

00:03:53.444 --> 00:03:58.040
It's equally likely that Y = 2x and
Y = one-half X, so that's just one-half.

00:03:58.040 --> 00:04:04.244
Plus, in this case, Y is X over 2,
so we're gonna get E of X over 2,

00:04:05.389 --> 00:04:08.875
Probability, or that's one-half again.

00:04:08.875 --> 00:04:12.812
And if you simply this,
you can take out the 2,

00:04:12.812 --> 00:04:18.376
take out the one-half,
simplify you get five-fourths E(x).

00:04:18.376 --> 00:04:22.230
All right, so
then the question is how to resolve this?

00:04:23.290 --> 00:04:24.490
Well, first of all,

00:04:24.490 --> 00:04:28.170
is there any case in which both of
these statements could be true?

00:04:31.141 --> 00:04:32.451
Someone said 0.

00:04:32.451 --> 00:04:37.950
Well, kinda, yeah, both envelopes have $0,
then that would be okay.

00:04:37.950 --> 00:04:42.930
Now, so let's assume there is a positive,
nonzero amount of money in both envelopes.

00:04:44.580 --> 00:04:45.779
Are there any other case?

00:04:48.788 --> 00:04:52.917
Infinity, well, infinity equals infinity,

00:04:52.917 --> 00:04:56.746
infinity equals five-fourths infinity.

00:04:56.746 --> 00:04:59.830
So one way out out it,
could we just say, well, on average,

00:04:59.830 --> 00:05:04.640
there's an infinite amount of money,
and then you're pretty happy, right?

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:08.353
But there are not many kinda like
the Saint Petersburg paradox,

00:05:08.353 --> 00:05:10.633
where the expected value is infinity.

00:05:10.633 --> 00:05:15.079
But there are not many real world
scenarios that you could think of,

00:05:15.079 --> 00:05:21.040
probably, where your expected value of
how much you'll make is infinity dollars.

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:25.790
So let's assume that these
numbers are not 0 or infinity.

00:05:25.790 --> 00:05:28.390
In that case,
this is just a direct contradiction,

00:05:28.390 --> 00:05:30.500
meaning that one of these
two things must be wrong.

00:05:32.900 --> 00:05:39.530
Well, symmetry, I can't find any way
to argue against the symmetry here.

00:05:39.530 --> 00:05:42.700
So, this has to be right.

00:05:42.700 --> 00:05:44.790
Symmetry takes precedence.

00:05:44.790 --> 00:05:47.919
So let's try to see what's
wrong with argument two.

00:05:47.919 --> 00:05:53.835
Well, actually,
this is one of the most common and

00:05:53.835 --> 00:05:58.928
troublesome mistakes with conditioning is

00:05:58.928 --> 00:06:06.238
to kind of like use the information,
and then forget about it.

00:06:06.238 --> 00:06:11.944
Look at what we did here,
we plugged in the information Y=2x,

00:06:11.944 --> 00:06:15.020
but then the condition went away.

00:06:17.330 --> 00:06:18.830
What's the justification for that?

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:26.180
There is none, it just looked good to
say that, but there's no justification.

00:06:26.180 --> 00:06:32.164
So, actually this step is wrong.

00:06:32.164 --> 00:06:34.390
So, actually it's not equal.

00:06:35.450 --> 00:06:39.930
What we should have written was,
it's perfectly valid to plug in the 2x.

00:06:39.930 --> 00:06:42.230
Let's write the corrected version.

00:06:43.470 --> 00:06:45.711
It's perfectly valid to plug in 2x, but

00:06:45.711 --> 00:06:48.604
that doesn't mean we can
forget that we know Y=2x.

00:06:48.604 --> 00:06:51.056
So, it's 2x given Y= 2x.

00:06:51.056 --> 00:06:55.272
And similarly over here,
we can plug in the information, but

00:06:55.272 --> 00:06:59.180
it doesn't mean we're not
conditioning on it anymore.

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:05.330
So, we can do that.

00:07:05.330 --> 00:07:10.170
But we still have to then evaluate
this conditional expectation.

00:07:10.170 --> 00:07:15.028
We can't just say that we can
forget this information here.

00:07:15.028 --> 00:07:17.030
In fact, there's no more justification for

00:07:17.030 --> 00:07:21.520
forgetting this information here,
then there would be up here.

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:23.950
You just can't say that.

00:07:23.950 --> 00:07:28.308
So actually what we just showed is that

00:07:28.308 --> 00:07:37.653
essentially, E(X|Y=2x),

00:07:40.418 --> 00:07:46.950
Is not equal to E of,
let's do it this way,

00:07:46.950 --> 00:07:53.490
E(Y|Y=2x) is not equal to E(2x).

00:07:53.490 --> 00:07:57.340
So what's going on there is I
like to think of this in terms of

00:07:57.340 --> 00:07:59.710
indicator random variables.

00:07:59.710 --> 00:08:03.225
So let's just let I be
the indicator random variable.

00:08:03.225 --> 00:08:08.601
I is the indicator of which envelope has
more money, so we could say I is one,

00:08:08.601 --> 00:08:14.313
if y equals 2x, and zero otherwise, or
we could define it the other way around.

00:08:15.614 --> 00:08:19.556
That's the event that says that the
envelope on the right has twice as much

00:08:19.556 --> 00:08:21.500
money as the one on the left, okay.

00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:23.560
So we have an indicator for that.

00:08:24.780 --> 00:08:32.760
Then, essentially what we just showed
is that X and I are dependent.

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:37.090
We can either talk about X and
I or talk about Y and I.

00:08:37.090 --> 00:08:40.510
They're dependent, and
that seems surprising at first.

00:08:43.195 --> 00:08:48.060
So let's think about what that means.

00:08:48.060 --> 00:08:54.798
It says that if you got to observe X, then
somehow that gives information about I.

00:08:54.798 --> 00:08:57.799
So now we get to think
of more about the case,

00:08:57.799 --> 00:09:02.280
what happens if you actually get
to open the envelope on the left?

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:04.450
Okay, and you see $100 there.

00:09:04.450 --> 00:09:09.238
So you know the other one is 50 or
200, but the question is whether that

00:09:09.238 --> 00:09:14.190
changes your probabilities for I,
that is, is the other one 200 or 50?

00:09:14.190 --> 00:09:16.200
Is saying it's not 50,50 anymore.

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:20.200
Which seems a little strange because

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:23.650
you're not given any information
kind of the scale of the problem.

00:09:23.650 --> 00:09:29.200
So let's say you open envelope on the left
and there's a trillion dollars there.

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:34.010
Well probably you're really happy,
but is a trillion a big number,

00:09:34.010 --> 00:09:35.870
or a small number?

00:09:35.870 --> 00:09:41.290
Well it's a lot of money, but in the grand
scheme of things, compared to the entire

00:09:41.290 --> 00:09:46.560
real line, from zero to infinity,
a trillion is miniscule, right?

00:09:46.560 --> 00:09:50.440
A trillion is nothing compared to other
numbers I could name if I wanted.

00:09:50.440 --> 00:09:52.800
So when you see that trillion dollars,

00:09:53.830 --> 00:09:56.920
does that give you information that
makes you think that the other one is

00:09:56.920 --> 00:09:59.690
probably only half a trillion
cuz a trillion is big?

00:10:00.730 --> 00:10:02.590
What's a trillion, right?

00:10:02.590 --> 00:10:08.700
It's nothing compared 2 to the 2 to
the 2 to the trillion to the trillion or

00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:10.000
something like that.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.610
But if you would observe that
then that's nothing compared to

00:10:12.610 --> 00:10:13.800
other numbers I could name.

00:10:14.980 --> 00:10:18.450
So it seems surprising that they're
dependent, but essentially we just proved

00:10:18.450 --> 00:10:22.910
that they have to be dependent if
the expected values are finite.

00:10:24.490 --> 00:10:28.410
And there's a strategic practice
that's related to this too,

00:10:28.410 --> 00:10:32.790
which says that, you can look up
the problem if you haven't already.

00:10:32.790 --> 00:10:36.530
But just to tell you what the result of
that problem is, which is also surprising.

00:10:36.530 --> 00:10:39.120
It also is a two envelope problem,
but in that problem

00:10:39.120 --> 00:10:42.570
it just assumes that there's two amounts
of money, two positive amounts of money.

00:10:42.570 --> 00:10:44.600
It's not assumed that
one is double the other.

00:10:44.600 --> 00:10:49.200
And the problem is to come up with
a strategy guaranteed to give you

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:53.340
better than a 50% chance of getting
the envelope with more money.

00:10:53.340 --> 00:10:56.560
You get to observe one and
then you choose whether to switch.

00:10:56.560 --> 00:11:02.390
You can guarantee that your probability of
success is strictly greater than one half.

00:11:02.390 --> 00:11:04.396
Which again, at first sounds impossible.

00:11:04.396 --> 00:11:08.940
Because if it's a trillion dollars,
should you switch or not?

00:11:09.940 --> 00:11:13.140
But it says in a certain
sense that actually you can.

00:11:14.430 --> 00:11:18.160
You can make a measure of is a trillion
a big number or a small number.

00:11:18.160 --> 00:11:23.810
And the strategy is in that problem,
is to generate your own random threshold.

00:11:23.810 --> 00:11:26.500
That is generate some value t,

00:11:26.500 --> 00:11:29.640
let's say from an exponential
distribution, but it doesn't have to be.

00:11:29.640 --> 00:11:31.050
You can pick some other distribution.

00:11:31.050 --> 00:11:33.390
You generate your own threshold value and

00:11:33.390 --> 00:11:36.900
then you say you're happy if you got more
then t and unhappy if you get less then t,

00:11:36.900 --> 00:11:39.490
and that gives you better
then a 50% chance of success.

00:11:41.400 --> 00:11:44.510
All right, so anyway,
that's the two envelope problem.

00:11:44.510 --> 00:11:49.000
There's many, many different articles and
debates about this.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:53.036
And some people try to take Bayesian
approaches to resolving this and so on.

00:11:53.036 --> 00:11:55.479
But I think that's fairly unnecessary,

00:11:55.479 --> 00:11:58.075
I think the key blunder
is just in this step.

00:11:58.075 --> 00:12:01.058
And this is kind of a strange problem, but

00:12:01.058 --> 00:12:05.080
this mistake comes up in a lot
of other contexts as well.

00:12:05.080 --> 00:12:07.250
So it's worth thinking carefully about.

00:12:07.250 --> 00:12:09.040
We plugged in the information, but

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:11.620
that doesn't mean we can then
get rid of the information.

00:12:11.620 --> 00:12:14.640
The only time when we can get rid
of the stuff we're conditioning on

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:16.460
is when we know we have independence.

00:12:17.610 --> 00:12:22.440
And here there was no justification for
independence and in fact, X and I, or

00:12:22.440 --> 00:12:24.140
Y and I can't be independent.

00:12:25.310 --> 00:12:26.457
Which is not obvious.

00:12:26.457 --> 00:12:28.655
It's not obvious that
they're not independent, but

00:12:28.655 --> 00:12:31.870
on the other hand you can't just say
they're independent without proving it.

00:12:31.870 --> 00:12:35.400
And if you try to prove it you'll find
they actually are not independent here.

00:12:35.400 --> 00:12:37.350
So that's what's going
on with that problem.

