Y, it's just a function of little x.

00:34:29.470 --> 00:34:30.440
It might be a constant.

00:34:31.480 --> 00:34:33.065
If X and Y are independent,

00:34:33.065 --> 00:34:37.620
then conditioning on X gives
us no information about Y.

00:34:37.620 --> 00:34:43.000
So if they're independent, this will just
reduce to E of Y, which is a constant

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:48.460
function, but it has to be a function of
x, possibly a constant function, okay.

00:34:48.460 --> 00:34:51.550
So that's just to emphasize
that's a function of x.

00:34:51.550 --> 00:34:55.410
But that also suggests how to define

00:34:55.410 --> 00:35:00.430
conditional expectation
given a random variable.

00:35:00.430 --> 00:35:05.281
So we wanted to find E
of Y given capital X,

00:35:08.444 --> 00:35:11.857
As g of X, capital X now.

00:35:11.857 --> 00:35:17.714
[COUGH] So I mean this is like not
a complicated looking equation, but

00:35:17.714 --> 00:35:23.390
conceptually, this takes a lot
of thought and I'll explain it.

00:35:23.390 --> 00:35:26.330
And I'll explain it more
in the next lecture.

00:35:26.330 --> 00:35:27.020
But really,

00:35:27.020 --> 00:35:31.390
you just have to take some time to just
think about what these things mean.

00:35:31.390 --> 00:35:34.176
I think carefully about it
because there's just so

00:35:34.176 --> 00:35:39.760
many mistakes you could fall into we don't
fully understand what this notation means.

00:35:39.760 --> 00:35:44.980
All right, so what this thing means
is we have this function of little x,

00:35:44.980 --> 00:35:53.080
and we replace little x by big X,
after evaluating it, not before.

00:35:53.080 --> 00:35:56.700
So one trap you could
fall into here is to say,

00:35:56.700 --> 00:36:01.650
well, g of capital,
this is g of little x, g of capital X,

00:36:01.650 --> 00:36:05.810
then I should plug in big X for
everywhere I see a little x.

00:36:05.810 --> 00:36:08.700
So I plug it in there and there, but

00:36:08.700 --> 00:36:13.750
in that case you would be saying
EY given capital X = capital X.

00:36:13.750 --> 00:36:17.200
And then you'd say, well,
I already knew capital X = capital X.

00:36:17.200 --> 00:36:22.570
So that's just irrelevant information that
I'll cross out and you'll get E of Y.

00:36:22.570 --> 00:36:24.580
That's not what this means.

00:36:24.580 --> 00:36:25.990
What it means is,

00:36:27.400 --> 00:36:30.560
think of this as a function of little
x that you've actually computed.

00:36:30.560 --> 00:36:32.380
Like, maybe it's x squared.

00:36:32.380 --> 00:36:34.700
I'll just write this as an example.

00:36:34.700 --> 00:36:39.590
So what it means is if g
of x little x = x squared.

00:36:40.670 --> 00:36:44.910
Then g of big X = big X squared.

00:36:46.220 --> 00:36:49.260
That's all it means,
that this is some function of X.

00:36:49.260 --> 00:36:53.980
And you replace little x by big X after
we actually have our hands on that

00:36:53.980 --> 00:36:55.269
function, okay?

00:36:55.269 --> 00:36:58.870
It's really just a notational trap
to think of plugging in the x here.

00:36:58.870 --> 00:37:02.970
But think of this as some function
you're replacing little x by big X.

00:37:02.970 --> 00:37:05.080
Notice that that's a random variable.

00:37:05.080 --> 00:37:12.136
So in particular,
E of Y given X is a random variable.

00:37:15.665 --> 00:37:19.700
It's a random variable
that's a function of x.

00:37:19.700 --> 00:37:23.519
It's not a function of y,
it's a function of x.

00:37:24.701 --> 00:37:29.626
All right, so the intuition for
that is that,

00:37:29.626 --> 00:37:33.290
I mean this is the definition.

00:37:33.290 --> 00:37:38.220
But the intuitive interpretation
is that E of Y given X,

00:37:39.420 --> 00:37:43.540
what that means is X is a random variable.

00:37:43.540 --> 00:37:48.630
But let's pretend that we observed X,
and we know what X is, and

00:37:48.630 --> 00:37:53.630
we then get to treat X as if it's
a known constant, that's what this says.

00:37:53.630 --> 00:37:57.430
So, it says assuming we get
to pretend that X is known,

00:37:57.430 --> 00:37:59.700
then what's our best prediction of Y?

00:38:00.940 --> 00:38:04.030
So that's allowed to be
a function of capital X, okay?

00:38:04.030 --> 00:38:06.870
So that's what it means intuitively.

00:38:06.870 --> 00:38:09.090
It's not really that
different from this and

00:38:09.090 --> 00:38:12.070
in fact when you have a problem like this,
you can always at

00:38:12.070 --> 00:38:15.840
least in principle translate it
back into conditioning on an event.

00:38:15.840 --> 00:38:19.613
It's just that the notation can
gets more unwieldy in this case.

00:38:19.613 --> 00:38:22.681
And we'll see examples where
it's just a lot more compact and

00:38:22.681 --> 00:38:26.584
convenient to write things this way than
always having to revert back to this.

00:38:26.584 --> 00:38:30.199
But if you start getting
confused about what this means,

00:38:30.199 --> 00:38:34.201
then you probably should revert
back to this kind of notation.

00:38:34.201 --> 00:38:38.778
Okay, so all right, so
let's do a couple of examples.

00:38:43.804 --> 00:38:50.790
So, Let's do one with Poissons.

00:38:50.790 --> 00:38:56.544
So let's let X and Y iid,

00:38:56.544 --> 00:39:02.585
I-I-D Poisson lambda.

00:39:02.585 --> 00:39:07.626
So all right, so suppose we

00:39:07.626 --> 00:39:12.895
wanna find E of X + Y given X.

00:39:14.830 --> 00:39:21.050
So, as I said, if we want, we could
first find this given big X = little x.

00:39:21.050 --> 00:39:24.850
And then change little x to big X and
you'll get the same thing.

00:39:24.850 --> 00:39:28.290
But, just for practice, let's do this
directly using the interpretation I

00:39:28.290 --> 00:39:33.030
mentioned, that this says we get
to pretend that we know X now.

00:39:33.030 --> 00:39:36.600
All right, so linearity still holds.

00:39:36.600 --> 00:39:40.694
So this is E of X given
X + E of Y given X.

00:39:42.924 --> 00:39:44.660
We can still use linearity.

00:39:44.660 --> 00:39:48.776
The reason is that conditional
probabilities are probabilities, right?

00:39:48.776 --> 00:39:52.090
So conditional probabilities
satisfies all the same rules and

00:39:52.090 --> 00:39:54.280
properties as probability.

00:39:54.280 --> 00:39:57.030
But therefore, since conditional
expectation is defined in terms of

00:39:57.030 --> 00:40:01.610
conditional probability,
conditional expectations are expectations.

00:40:01.610 --> 00:40:08.220
It satisfies the same properties such as
linearity So linearity is still true.

00:40:08.220 --> 00:40:10.705
Okay, so now let's just think about,
what does this thing actually mean?

00:40:10.705 --> 00:40:18.300
E(X|X), that's easy, that's X,
right, what else could it be?

00:40:18.300 --> 00:40:23.854
I know X and I want to predict X,
I'm gonna use X as my prediction.

00:40:23.854 --> 00:40:27.745
So okay, it has to be that.

00:40:27.745 --> 00:40:29.066
&gt;&gt; No.

00:40:29.066 --> 00:40:31.531
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]
&gt;&gt; Now let's think about E(Y|X).

00:40:33.898 --> 00:40:37.060
X and Y, I said they're iid,
so they're independent.

00:40:38.392 --> 00:40:40.970
Since they're independent,

00:40:40.970 --> 00:40:46.527
that means that getting to know X is
of no use at all in predicting Y.

00:40:46.527 --> 00:40:50.651
So that's just the same thing as E(Y).

00:40:50.651 --> 00:40:56.205
So this part is by independence, and
this part is X, X is a function of itself.

00:41:02.917 --> 00:41:07.860
In general, we'll talk more about this
later, but I may as well mention it now.

00:41:07.860 --> 00:41:12.077
If we have E(h(x)|x), this is true for
any problem, not just the Poisson, so

00:41:12.077 --> 00:41:13.539
I'm putting it above this.

00:41:13.539 --> 00:41:16.795
We'll come back to this later,
but since it's already coming up.

00:41:16.795 --> 00:41:21.493
If we get to know, h is any function,
we get to know X, well then we know h(x),

00:41:21.493 --> 00:41:23.192
so we could just compute it.

00:41:23.192 --> 00:41:27.531
So E(h(x)|x) = h(X), right?

00:41:27.531 --> 00:41:33.820
Cuz we have X, we have h(x) so
that's it, no uncertainty about it.

00:41:33.820 --> 00:41:37.946
Okay so E(X|X) is X,
E(Y|X) is just E(Y), so

00:41:37.946 --> 00:41:43.890
that's just X + lambda,
For the Poisson case.

00:41:43.890 --> 00:41:49.411
Actually, up to this point, I'm not using
anything in particular about Poisson,

00:41:49.411 --> 00:41:53.393
I'm only using the fact that
they're independent, okay?

00:41:53.393 --> 00:42:00.258
So that's just an example that shows,
okay, we can still use linearity.

00:42:00.258 --> 00:42:03.350
If we have independence, we can drop
the stuff we're conditioning on.

00:42:04.810 --> 00:42:07.287
And if we have something
that's completely known,

00:42:07.287 --> 00:42:10.168
then we can actually just take it out,
because it's known.

00:42:10.168 --> 00:42:15.536
All right,
now let's do the kind of reverse problem,

00:42:15.536 --> 00:42:19.983
suppose we were asked to find E(X|X+Y).

00:42:23.500 --> 00:42:28.071
And okay, so there's no form
of linearity that says this

00:42:28.071 --> 00:42:30.937
E(X) given this plus E(X|Y).

00:42:30.937 --> 00:42:35.074
And I've seen that mistake several times,
maybe, in time pressure-type of panic.

00:42:35.074 --> 00:42:40.408
Just, linearity is like this,
no, we can't do that here.

00:42:40.408 --> 00:42:44.933
Okay, so
we have to think about what this means.

00:42:44.933 --> 00:42:48.223
So I'll show you two ways to do this,
actually.

00:42:48.223 --> 00:42:54.806
One way is just straight
from the definition.

00:42:54.806 --> 00:43:01.999
We're gonna let T = X + Y and let's find
the conditional distribution, right?

00:43:01.999 --> 00:43:05.417
Because what this says is we
get to know the value of T, and

00:43:05.417 --> 00:43:09.495
then we use the conditional
distribution rather than the, right?

00:43:09.495 --> 00:43:11.726
Without this it would say just
the unconditional, right,

00:43:11.726 --> 00:43:14.070
what's the expected value,
we know it's lambda.

00:43:14.070 --> 00:43:17.417
But given this information, right,

00:43:17.417 --> 00:43:22.132
treating T as known,
then we need a conditional PMF.

00:43:22.132 --> 00:43:29.307
So, find the conditional PMF, Okay,

00:43:29.307 --> 00:43:34.440
so this is similar to
other problems we've seen,

00:43:34.440 --> 00:43:38.730
but let's just compute it for practice.

00:43:38.730 --> 00:43:41.770
We need the conditional PMF.

00:43:41.770 --> 00:43:47.128
We want the probability that X equals k,
let's say,

00:43:47.128 --> 00:43:51.900
given that T equals some number,
let's say n.

00:43:53.995 --> 00:43:57.330
Those are just dummy variables here,
I'm just finding the conditional PMF.

00:43:57.330 --> 00:44:02.174
That is, what's the distribution of X,
given that we know T, okay?

00:44:02.174 --> 00:44:07.453
So by Bayes' rule, that's just

00:44:07.453 --> 00:44:12.354
P(T = n | X = k) P(X = k),

00:44:12.354 --> 00:44:16.136
divided by P(T = n).

00:44:16.136 --> 00:44:21.477
And that's actually an easy calculation,
because T, this is another

00:44:21.477 --> 00:44:26.924
example of like that plugging in
thing with the two-envelope problem.

00:44:26.924 --> 00:44:32.333
T is X + Y, so we're gonna plug X = k,
and so we know that Y = n- k.

00:44:32.333 --> 00:44:36.331
And then in this case, we do get to cross
out this information at that point,

00:44:36.331 --> 00:44:38.440
because X and Y are independent.

00:44:38.440 --> 00:44:40.852
This would fail if
they're not independent.

00:44:40.852 --> 00:44:46.540
But in this case, X and Y are independent,

00:44:46.540 --> 00:44:51.280
so really this is just P(Y = n- k)

00:44:51.280 --> 00:44:55.864
P(X =k) divided by P(T = n).

00:44:55.864 --> 00:45:00.685
And sorry, we're going right to left here,
let's just write what is this here.

00:45:00.685 --> 00:45:05.740
Y = n- k,
just straight from the Poisson, right?

00:45:05.740 --> 00:45:12.620
E to the -lambda,
lambda to the n- k over (n- k) factorial.

00:45:15.230 --> 00:45:22.620
X is also Poisson, e to the -lambda,
lambda to the k over k factorial.

00:45:22.620 --> 00:45:27.350
And in the denominator, we know that the
sum of independent Poissons is Poisson.

00:45:27.350 --> 00:45:30.620
So this is gonna be a Poisson
of 2 lambda in the denominator.

00:45:30.620 --> 00:45:35.688
So we know that's e to the -2 lambda,

00:45:35.688 --> 00:45:41.689
(2 lambda) to the n
divided by n factorial.

00:45:41.689 --> 00:45:44.890
Okay, and if we simplify this,

00:45:44.890 --> 00:45:49.754
we get a very familiar-looking
distribution,

00:45:49.754 --> 00:45:53.441
right, what distribution is this?

00:45:53.441 --> 00:45:54.525
&gt;&gt; Binomial.

00:45:54.525 --> 00:45:59.770
&gt;&gt; Binomial, notice the e to
the -2 lambdas cancel, right?

00:46:00.880 --> 00:46:03.138
And these power of lambdas cancel, right,

00:46:03.138 --> 00:46:05.467
there's lambda to the n
over lambda to the n.

00:46:05.467 --> 00:46:08.440
We just have a one-half to the n here,
right?

00:46:08.440 --> 00:46:12.920
And this thing, n factorial,
put that on top, that's just n choose k.

00:46:12.920 --> 00:46:14.820
So this thing,
I'll simplify it one more step,

00:46:14.820 --> 00:46:18.850
it's just n choose k one-half to the n,
that's just a binomial.

00:46:20.050 --> 00:46:26.514
Okay, so what we just showed with that,
Bayes' rule,

00:46:26.514 --> 00:46:33.680
is that X|T = n is binomial
with parameters n and one-half.

00:46:36.050 --> 00:46:39.750
So now, let's use this to get
the conditional expectation.

00:46:39.750 --> 00:46:43.182
So what that says is E(X | X + Y), but

00:46:43.182 --> 00:46:47.870
let's first do the case of
conditioning on an event.

00:46:47.870 --> 00:46:51.518
So we're given T = n,
well that just says, given T = n,

00:46:51.518 --> 00:46:55.540
it's no longer Possion now, it's binomial.

00:46:55.540 --> 00:47:00.479
The expected value of this
binomial is just n over 2.

00:47:00.479 --> 00:47:06.932
So in the other notation,
this is conditioning on an event, right?

00:47:06.932 --> 00:47:12.271
But if we want to condition on T instead,
E(X|T), then all we have

00:47:12.271 --> 00:47:18.060
to do is replace this n by T,
just according to that definition there.

00:47:18.060 --> 00:47:19.995
So that's gonna be T over 2.

00:47:21.350 --> 00:47:24.061
So it says that if we
get to know the total,

00:47:24.061 --> 00:47:27.370
then our best prediction is 1/2 the total.

00:47:27.370 --> 00:47:30.891
That's actually a pretty intuitive result,
right?

00:47:30.891 --> 00:47:34.423
That we get to know the total of X and
Y, and they're iid, and

00:47:34.423 --> 00:47:37.003
we wanna predict
the average of one of them.

00:47:37.003 --> 00:47:40.099
Well, if I told you the total was 100,
and they're iid,

00:47:40.099 --> 00:47:43.280
you'd probably guess that they're each 50,
right?

00:47:43.280 --> 00:47:45.310
That would be a reasonable guess.

00:47:45.310 --> 00:47:48.880
So that's a mathematical proof that
that's kinda the correct guess.

00:47:48.880 --> 00:47:53.107
That's one way to prove it,
here's a way that I like even more,

00:47:53.107 --> 00:47:54.923
is to notice the symmetry.

00:47:54.923 --> 00:48:00.193
E(X | X + Y) = E (Y | X +

00:48:00.193 --> 00:48:05.007
Y) is true by symmetry,

00:48:05.007 --> 00:48:09.604
because they're iid.

00:48:16.797 --> 00:48:22.732
This is always true with iid, that doesn't
assume anything about the Possion.

00:48:22.732 --> 00:48:27.135
Lets add these two things,

00:48:27.135 --> 00:48:32.495
E(X | X + Y) + E(Y | X + Y),

00:48:32.495 --> 00:48:39.587
by linearity, that's E(X + Y | X + Y).

00:48:39.587 --> 00:48:45.390
But E(X + Y | X + Y) is X + Y, which is T.

00:48:47.900 --> 00:48:52.046
So I added something plus itself and
I got this, so

00:48:52.046 --> 00:48:57.500
that immediately implies the same result,
E(X|T) = T/2.

00:48:57.500 --> 00:49:00.368
And this didn't use anything
about the Poisson, so

00:49:00.368 --> 00:49:02.672
that's actually a more general result.

00:49:02.672 --> 00:49:08.370
All right, lastly let me just mention one
key property that his notation gives us,

00:49:08.370 --> 00:49:09.730
we'll prove it next time.

00:49:11.080 --> 00:49:15.099
So this is called iterated expectation, or

00:49:15.099 --> 00:49:21.302
it's also called Adam's law for
reasons I'll tell you next time.

00:49:21.302 --> 00:49:24.131
This is the single most important
property of conditional expectation.

00:49:24.131 --> 00:49:25.864
So it's good to be aware of it now, and

00:49:25.864 --> 00:49:28.370
then I'll talk in detail
of that next time.

00:49:28.370 --> 00:49:33.140
It just says, as I said, E(Y|X) is a
random variable, so we might want to know,

00:49:33.140 --> 00:49:35.690
what's the expected value
of that random variable?

00:49:35.690 --> 00:49:40.410
Well, if you do E(E(Y|X)), you get E(Y).

00:49:40.410 --> 00:49:45.670
And this is closely related to
the law of total probability.

00:49:45.670 --> 00:49:48.970
In a sense, it's a very compact way of
writing the law of total probability,

00:49:48.970 --> 00:49:50.740
extremely useful fact.

00:49:50.740 --> 00:49:52.100
All right, so
I'll see you all on Wednesday.

